      <div class="msgContentFrame"><div class="msgQuote"><div class="source">justpassingthrough1 wrote:</div><div class="orig">Ruisu ponders : &quot;Wonder what'll propel RMT into success in XIV...&quot; <br /> <br />Ruisu I refer you back to Mecklore : <br />&quot;Three easy steps to keep RMT from ruining our game  <br /> <br />1. STOP BUYING GIL !!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!  <br />2. STOP BUYING GIL !!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!  <br />3. STOP BUYING GIL !!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!  <br /> <br />They only exist because we buy their products.&quot; <br /> <br />and Toshio : <br />&quot;The solution to RMT: ban the players who buy gil.&quot;</div></div>Rarity-based economies will always favor RMT. I saw it in Lineage II, I saw it in RO, and I saw it in FFXI. And if SE has learned nothing from FFXI, then I'll see it again in FFXIV. The reason I brought up WoW is because item acquisition in that game is not about how rare a piece of gear is, but how much time you put into getting the gear. And the best part is that none of it can be sold because it is bound to you. There was no PCC idiocy in WoW. No people killing each other over leaping boots. No people pos-botting to kill the NM for Ochiudo's Kote, because uber gear existed at the high levels, was all bound to you and required time with no RNG involved. Crafting materials were relatively accessible to anyone leveling a craft instead of being so stupidly rare you'd see ridiculous price hikes in the AH. <br /> <br />Again, all that combined is why RMT presence in WoW is very minimal. There's nothing for them to monopolize in the game. Easier to implement and certainly a lot cheaper than having to hire a group of people to solely monitor every trade and transaction going on in-game.<div class="msgSig"><div class="msgSigBar sm">----------------------------</div><a href="HTTP://yare-yare.com/beseiged.jpg" rel="external nofollow" title="yare-yare.com/beseiged.jpg">Beseiged</a> <br /><div class="msgQuote"><d